Data

For this homework, we will use amniota data from: Myhrvold N, Baldridge E, Chan B, Sivam D, Freeman DL, Ernest SKM (2015). An amniote life-history database to perform comparative analyses with birds, mammals, and reptiles. Ecology, 96, 3109. doi: 10.1890/15-0846.1 (URL: https://doi.org/10.1890/15-0846.1).

  1. Make any necessary replacements in the data such that all NAs appear as NA.
amniota_all_nas <- amniota %>%
  replace_with_na_all(condition = ~.x %in% c(common_na_numbers, common_na_strings))

  1. Use naniar to visualize the number of NAs in each variable. Which variables have the most NAs?
gg_miss_var(amniota_all_nas)

Subspecies and female body mass at maturity are the top two variables in the data that have the most amount of NAs.

  1. Calculate the number of NAs in the egg_mass_g column sorted by taxonomic class; i.e.how many NAs are present in the egg_mass_g column in birds, mammals, and reptiles? Does this results make sense biologically? How do these results affect your interpretation of NAs?
amniota_all_nas %>%
  group_by(class) %>%
  select(class, egg_mass_g) %>%
  miss_var_summary() %>%
  arrange(desc(n_miss))
## # A tibble: 3  4
## # Groups:   class [3]
##   class    variable   n_miss pct_miss
##   <chr>    <chr>       <int>    <num>
## 1 Reptilia egg_mass_g   6040     92.0
## 2 Mammalia egg_mass_g   4953    100  
## 3 Aves     egg_mass_g   4927     50.3

This makes sense because it is significantly more easier to measure bird eggs than reptile eggs due to the size difference. These values can also help us represent values that we physically cannot measure, such as mammal eggs.
